<subSubSection id="C368650B322E9835FF481095FD55FE2A" pageId="37" pageNumber="94" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCD3680322E9835FF481095FD55FE2A" blockId="37.[151,1437,402,2011]" pageId="37" pageNumber="94">
<emphasis id="B906EA92322E9835FF481095FEA2FE72" bold="true" box="[151,286,402,427]" pageId="37" pageNumber="94">Etymology.</emphasis>
Bellatrix is latin for “female warrior”, stressing the fact that only females were available for the study. The word 
<taxonomicName id="4C724D03322E9835FED610B1FEDBFE17" authorityName="Sassi" authorityYear="2018" box="[265,359,438,462]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Metallactus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellatrix">
<emphasis id="B906EA92322E9835FED610B1FEDBFE17" box="[265,359,438,462]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="94">bellatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is intended here as a noun in the nominative singular, standing in apposition to the generic name (articles 11.9.1.2 and 31.2.1 of I.C.Z.N., 4th edition).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
